<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I can't believe the selfish stubbornness I'm reading from some of the clerics here.  It reminds me of the posts on another thread that went, "You want Symbol, you can bloody well pay for it yourself" -- as if the survival of someone else in your party were not a serious matter to you.  If I were that group's leader, I'd start looking to replace that cleric.<P>Healing a pet is not the cleric's priority?  Pets can deal out huge amounts of damage.  You're forgetting to calculate that the sooner a mob dies, the less damage everyone in your party takes, and the less mana it costs you.  That mage's pet probably dealt out nearly as much damage as the monks, and the cleric should have seen it as a very important member of the group.  It should have been Reso'd and Armored and, since they were hunting in BugsAndBats, probably even Symboled.  Then it might not have needed a heal at all.<P>For the rest of you dopes who "don't like pets much", consider this: with the two monks dealing damage, a certain mob dies in thirty seconds but deals out damage the whole time.  Add just one mage or necro pet and the same mob dies in about twenty-two seconds.  Damage to party is reduced by almost a third.  Yeah, the dope who owns the pet can be incompetent and let it go wandering (let it die, please), or it can be an extremely mana-efficient addition to the party.<P>Of course you never heal a pet when your tank is dying.  That almost goes without saying.  But you people who discount the value of the pets aren't thinking clearly.<P>Perhaps there was a communication breakdown.  Most high-forties mages don't get upset over losing a few silver in malachite, so you might ask the real reason he was ticked.  You don't tell us how much mana the mage had at the end of the battle; was he out of mana mid-battle and incapable of replacing the pet?  That could be a serious loss to the party, then, and could have meant everyone's death.  <P>On a less desperate note: Perhaps he had had to cast that pet ten times to get a "high" one, in which case keeping it alive would be rather more important to him than seemed logical to you. (I'm inclined to agree with the mage on that one.) The pet's level has a lot to do with how much damage it doesn't take, just as a PC's level does.<P>Hope this makes a couple of you think twice about how valuable pets are.<P>--------------------<P>Ismena, 55 Cleric<BR>Alethea, 26 Bard<BR>Wynne, 19 Enchanter<BR>Prexus
