Can you imagine the backlash if there was a nasty fight and a cleric healed a pet while someone else died ? The pet is secondary to the group, no matter how much damage it dispenses. If there is time and mana, sure. The pet owner shouldn't expect it otherwise.<P>About druids and shamans as backup healers: I don't expect them to help me with heals, but it's nice if they can. I always call out my mana and if I get too low, I ask them (if they're around) if they can assist with heals. If they can, great. If not, I do whatever I can.<P>About Shamans that Cana: I know Shaman buffs are important as are Slows and what not. It irritates me tho, to have my (regular) shaman cana down to about 1 bubble of health and then ask me for a heal. The reason I don't like it is because he is making himself a liability.<P>Example: We were hunting in Dragon Necropolis. Many of the Chetari there will HT and then attack. Shaman canas down to 1.5 bubbles of health while we're waiting to make the next move. I'm medding. Roaming Chetari come up behind us, uses Harm Touch on the Shaman then walks up and kills him in two blows before anyone could react.<P>Cana is a good spell, but overused can put the group in an adverse situation.<P>He actually learned a lesson that night. His health now hovers around 60% - 70%. If he needs to cana more, he'll ask me if I have mana to heal him.<P><BR>Ugh. I went off on a tangent. Sorry this is so long. It's late. I'm tired.<P>^_^<P>--------------------<P>Xiaojie<BR>Band-Aid<BR>High Priestess of the Blackened Heart<BR>Terris Thule
