<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
Hmm...heal a monk that has just over 1k hps...or heal a pet that has about 2k hps.  Cheal would be more efficient, if the monk would learn to back up and let the pet tank!<P>Admittedly, healing a player always takes precidence over a pet when both are in need.  The value of the pet though, should not be underestimate.  High hit points, good damage output, and in the end, expendable if necessary.  <P>As far as the mage healing the pet goes, well, that was a useful tactic up until level 34 maybe.  After that, the 100 mana, 200 hp heal spell, just doesn't cut it, particularly on a pet that has over 2k hp.  In the time it takes to cast the spell, the pet has already more damage than that.<P>As far as targeting the pet goes, there is a common trick used on big raids with limited healers called reverse assisting.  You basically assist the bad guy to find out who he's beating on.  Apparently, the earth pet in this example was at least a primary tank, if not THE primary tank as it took enough damage to die.  The mage could have backed the pet out to save it, but then all the damage falls on the monk, and the pet is no longer contributing damage.<P>It's all situational.  If the monks were in good shape, keeping that extra damage dealer/tank around is always nice in case of those unexpected spawns.  I'd prefer to see a pet treated as a party member if it's doing any real tanking, with preference going to players of course.<P>--------------------<P>Bibbles Fuzzywumpus<BR>The Apothic Avenger<BR>Divine Wind - 54th Magician - Innoruuk
