<HR size="1" color="#dedfdf">
<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
I also play a cleric and a mage, so I have experience with both sides of the issue.  The people who say that priority for healing should go to a player and not a pet are correct, but there is more to the issue than that simple rule of thumb.  There are several basic considerations to keep in mind.<P>First, in a full group with plenty of tanks, and the pet isn't getting hit much, then it should be treated as completely expendable.  That's fine, it's serving as little more than a long-term dot in that situation.  However, in a group that isn't full, or is low on tanks, then that pet is an important "member of the team", so to speak.  Even if the pet isn't the only tank, if it is doing a sizeable share of the tanking, it should be healed as best the cleric is able to (keeping in mind the safety of the other players, of course).  The loss of a significant tank can easily add more grief to the players that are still alive than it's worth, even if that tank is a pet.<P>Secondly, there is the issue of mana efficiency.  Yes, a mage could just summon up another pet if the first one dies, but it's likely that the new pet won't be the best pet that they can cast.  If it isn't the highest level pet the mage has available, then that lower level pet will hit for less damage, have less hps, and will get hit more often. That's why you often see a mage casting pets over and over until they get a "good" one. Also, the pet will have to be rebuffed and re-equipped.  When I play a mage, I give my pets two summoned weapons for them to dual wield.  I also summon up necklaces and rings for them, to improve their ac.  These things improve the pet's tanking ability, but it's more mana down the drain if the pet dies.  Of course I could just make do with a substandard pet without the extra frills, but mobs will take longer to kill, and will end up costing more mana through the extra healing/nuking used while killing them.  <P>And yes, a mage has healing spells for their pets, but they are very mana inefficient, when compared to a cleric's spells.  This has already been mentioned.  If you said, as a cleric, that it's not your responsibility to keep the pet healthy, yes that's true.  But the same amount of mana that the mage burns to heal a pitiful amount of his pet's hps could instead be used to dish out a much greater amount of damage to the mob.  When a pet is playing a significant role as a tank... not even necessarily as primary tank, but as a significant member of the tanking team... it will take damage.  Without the cleric heal, the mage is left to decide what he will sacrifice: losing the highest level pet, plus the mana necessary to summon another (plus the mana for extra summons if he tries to get another high pet), plus the cost of rebuffing and re-equiping; or losing all the nuke damage he could have done to the mob keeping the pet up with his inefficient chain healing (which may be too little to keep the pet alive anyway).<P>Some mages choose a different strategy than mine.  They treat their pets as expendable, and chain-cast them as needed so that they don't have to worry about healing them or anything.  If you are grouped with a mage who follows this line of thought, you should definitely treat their pets as expendably as that mage does.  However, I prefer a strategy that emphasizes quality over quantity during the occasions when I'm grouped with a cleric, because I believe that this strategy is ultimately more mana- and time-efficient in the long run.  I can maximize my pet damage and tanking ability by using a max-level pet and summoned item-ac buffs, and a cleric can further supplement this high-quality approach by using their superior heals and buffing ability to ensure that the top-notch pet stays alive.<P>That's why when I play my cleric, and there is a pet class in the group, I do three things: First I look at the makeup of my party and decide if the pet is making a significant contribution as a tank.  If it's taking a good amount of damage, the answer is probably yes.  If it is, then I ask the mage if he takes a "quantity" or "quality" approach.  If he prefers to summon the best pet he has and keep it alive, then I treat it like it's any other tank, keeping in mind it should be the first tank to die.  I will even buff it like it's one of the tanks.  And once I've started to buff it, the mana efficiency argument to keep it alive takes on even more weight.<P>Again, this only applies when the pet is making a noticeable contribution in a tanking capacity.  Maybe this doesn't happen very often to other players.  It happens fairly often to me, though, and so this is what I tend to do.  And, despite the length of this post, I don't suppose it's all that important one way or another.  I just like to do things the best that I can, and that's my two cents worth.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">  Well, thank you all for listening, and I wish you all good luck!<P>--------------------<P>(Looks around at the battle carnage) Anyone else wanna negotiate?  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">
</FONT>
