<FONT SIZE="2" FACE="Verdana, Arial">
A few clarifications about the points raised by Azrath:<P>1. Yes, mages get heals, but as I explained in my previous post, I believe there are more efficient ways for them to spend their mana when they have a cleric around AND that cleric also has the mana available to heal the pet.<P>2. Yes, chain-casting a pet is an option, and if that is the option that the mage has chosen to follow, then so be it.  Personally I don't believe that this is always the most efficient method to follow. I won't re-explain why here, because it's in my first post (just look above this one. Yes, I know it's a long one  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">, but bear with it if this is a topic that really interests you).  Basically, keeping a top-notch pet that has already had a significant amount of mana invested in it can sometimes be more mana efficient in the long-run, as outlined above.<P>3. Of course the enchanter is needed more, by the entire group.  Nowhere did I suggest that the enchanter be deprived or endangered in any way. Or any other group member. What I DID try to say is that if the pet is playing a significant role as a tank, then the loss of that tank during a battle could endanger the entire group.  Including the enchanter.<P>Next you mention that pets have a very fast regen.  Yes, but I was not advocating that a cleric burn mana to "top off" a pet between pulls.  What I did suggest is that the cleric consider throwing a life-saving heal on the pet during the middle of the fight, if the pet is being an important tank and will die if it doesn't get it.<P>Also, I agree that a cleric shouldn't go out of their way to keep checking a pet's health, even when the pet is being a major tank.  If the mage is doing his job properly, he'll be keeping track of pet health himself and will notify the cleric that the pet needs a heal. On the other hand, the clerics who take the time to read these boards are probably the really good ones... the ones who will keep an eye on any battle factor that their gut tells them might affect their group's survival. I applaud anyone, of any class, who cares enough to develop those kinds of instincts and skills. <P>Finally, I think that the overall tone of Azrath's last paragraph contained an overly harsh attitude, in my opinion.  I agree with him that the mage that Enoob mentioned over-reacted a lot when his pet died.  He shouldn't have been so rude, or gotten so upset.  Things happen.  But I don't think that responding to people who act like that with the same bad attitude is going to accomplish anything productive.  I mean really, saying things like "they can die alone and get no reses from you"? Those are pretty harsh words.  Personally, I would try to work things out with a little polite communication, or just go my separate way if things couldn't be worked out satifactorily.  Be careful how you treat others; what goes around comes around, and people remember when you're smart and considerate and cool, just as much as when you're not.<P>Well, I'll step off my soapbox now.  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0"> Take care everyone, and I welcome all of your comments and opinions.<P>--------------------<P>(Looks around at the battle carnage) Anyone else wanna negotiate?  <IMG SRC="smile.gif" border="0">
</FONT>
